The issue you're encountering is common when linking static libraries with MSVC, especially when dealing with libraries built with different configurations. Here are several solutions to try:

## 1. Check Library Compilation Settings

First, ensure your libxml2 static library was built with compatible settings:

- **Same runtime library**: Make sure both your project and libxml2 are using the same runtime library (e.g., `/MT` for static runtime, `/MD` for dynamic)
- **Architecture match**: Both should be either 32-bit or 64-bit
- **Debug/Release consistency**: Debug builds should link with debug libraries, release with release

## 2. Modify Your Link Command

Try this link command instead:

```cmd
link test001.obj /NODEFAULTLIB:MSVCRT /LIBPATH:C:\libxml2vc\lib libxml2s.lib legacy_stdio_definitions.lib ws2_32.lib
```

The additional libraries are often needed:
- `legacy_stdio_definitions.lib` - Provides standard I/O functions
- `ws2_32.lib` - Windows sockets library (libxml2 may need network functions)

## 3. Add Required System Libraries

libxml2 typically requires these additional system libraries:

```cmd
link test001.obj /NODEFAULTLIB:MSVCRT /LIBPATH:C:\libxml2vc\lib libxml2s.lib ws2_32.lib advapi32.lib user32.lib
```

## 4. Check Your Source Code

Add these pragma directives at the top of your source file (before including libxml headers):

```c
#pragma comment(lib, "libxml2s.lib")
#pragma comment(lib, "ws2_32.lib")
#pragma comment(lib, "advapi32.lib")
#pragma comment(lib, "user32.lib")

#define LIBXML_STATIC  // This is crucial for static linking
#include <libxml/parser.h>
#include <libxml/tree.h>
```

## 5. Complete Compilation Example

Here's a complete compilation approach:

```cmd
# Compile
cl /c /I"C:\libxml2vc\include" test001.c

# Link with all required libraries
link test001.obj /LIBPATH:C:\libxml2vc\lib libxml2s.lib ws2_32.lib advapi32.lib user32.lib
```

## 6. If `streamFile` is Your Function

The `_streamFile` error suggests this might be a custom function. Make sure it's defined in your project:

```c
// Add this definition somewhere in your code
void streamFile(const char* filename) {
    // Your implementation
}
```

## 7. Verify Library Contents

Check if your symbols exist in the library using dumpbin:

```cmd
dumpbin /exports libxml2s.lib | findstr "xmlMemoryDump"
dumpbin /exports libxml2s.lib | findstr "xmlCleanupParser"
```

## Most Likely Solution

The key issues are probably:
1. Missing `LIBXML_STATIC` definition in your code
2. Missing system libraries (ws2_32.lib, etc.)
3. Runtime library mismatch

Try this approach first:

```c
#define LIBXML_STATIC
#include <libxml/parser.h>
#include <libxml/tree.h>

// Your code...
```

Then link with:
```cmd
link test001.obj /LIBPATH:C:\libxml2vc\lib libxml2s.lib ws2_32.lib advapi32.lib user32.lib
```

This should resolve the unresolved external symbols.

